.SH NAME
\f[B]zelta revert\f[R] \- Revert datasets to a previous snapshot state.
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]zelta revert\f[R] [\f[B]\-d\f[R] \f[I]depth\f[R]]
[\f[I]initiator\f[R]] \f[I]dataset[\(atsnapshot]\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]zelta revert\f[R] rolls back a dataset and all of its descendents
to a specified snapshot.
If no snapshot is provided, the most recent snapshot will be used.
.PP
Rollback operations are destructive and will permanently discard all
changes made after the snapshot.
Datasets must not be in active use.
Zelta does not automatically destroy dependent clones.
.SH OPTIONS
A \f[I]dataset\f[R] parameter is required.
.TP
\f[B]\f[BI]dataset[\(atsnapshot]\f[B]\f[R]
A dataset, optionally including a snapshot name, to which the dataset
tree will be reverted.
.TP
\f[B]initiator\f[R]
A remote host, accessible via SSH, where the revert commands will be
executed.
.TP
\f[B]\(enforce\f[R]
Force rollback even if newer snapshots exist.
.TP
\f[B]\-n, \(endryrun\f[R]
Don\(cqt revert, but show the \f[CR]zfs rollback\f[R] commands that
would be executed.
.TP
\f[B]\-q\f[R]
Reduce verbosity.
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R]
Increase verbosity.
.TP
\f[B]\-d \f[BI]depth\f[B], \(endepth \f[BI]depth\f[B]\f[R]
Limits the depth of all Zelta operations.
